Bluegrass music form American roots music was named Bill Monroe who named his band The Blue Grass Boys The Bluegrass boys played Mountain Music style that Bill learned Asheville North Carolina from bands like Wade Mainers and other popular acts radio station WWNC the 19391996 band Kentucky mandolin player and songwriter Bill Monroe who considered the father bluegrass was further developed musicians who played with him including 5string banjo player Earl Scruggs and guitarist Lester Flatt was then evolved other musicians who admired the highenergy instrumental and vocal music Monroes group created and who carried into new bands some which created subgenres bluegrass Bluegrass influenced the music Appalachia and other styles including gospel and jazz Appalachian music itself has mixed roots Irish Scottish and English traditional music and was also later influenced the music AfricanAmericans through incorporation jazz and blues elements Settlers from Britain and Ireland arrived Appalachia during the 18th century and brought with them the musical traditions their homelands These traditions consisted primarily English and Scottish balladswhich were essentially unaccompanied narrativeand dance music such Irish reels which were accompanied fiddle Many older bluegrass songs come directly from the British Isles Several Appalachian bluegrass ballads such Pretty Saro Cuckoo Bird and House Carpenter come from England and preserve the English ballad tradition both melodically and lyrically Others such The Two Sisters also come from England however the lyrics are about Ireland Some bluegrass fiddle songs popular Appalachia such Leather Britches and Pretty Polly have Scottish roots The dance tune Cumberland Gap may derived from the tune that accompanies the Scottish ballad Bonnie George Campbell bluegrass some forms jazz one more instruments each takes its turn playing the melody and improvising around while the others perform accompaniment this especially typified tunes called breakdowns This contrast oldtime music which all instruments play the melody together one instrument carries the lead throughout while the others provide accompaniment Breakdowns are often characterized rapid tempos and unusual instrumental dexterity and sometimes complex chord changes There are three major subgenres bluegrass Traditional bluegrass has musicians playing folk songs tunes with traditional chord progressions and using only acoustic instruments with example being Bill Monroe Progressive bluegrass groups may use electric instruments and import songs from other genres particularly rock roll Examples include Cadillac Sky and Bearfoot Another subgenre bluegrass gospel uses Christian lyrics soulful three fourpart harmony singing and sometimes the playing instrumentals newer development the bluegrass world Neotraditional bluegrass exemplified bands such The Grascals and Mountain Heart bands from this subgenre typically have more than one lead singer Bluegrass music has attracted diverse following worldwide Bluegrass pioneer Bill Monroe characterized the genre Scottish bagpipes and oletime fiddlin Its Methodist and Holiness and Baptist Its blues and jazz and has high lonesome sound Unlike mainstream country music bluegrass traditionally played acoustic stringed instruments The fiddle fivestring banjo guitar mandolin and upright bass string bass are often joined the resonator guitar also referred Dobro and occasionally harmonica Jews harp This instrumentation originated rural dance bands and the basis which the earliest bluegrass bands were formed The guitar now most commonly played with style referred flatpicking unlike the style early bluegrass guitarists such Lester Flatt who used thumb pick and finger pick Banjo players often use the threefinger picking style made popular banjoists such Earl Scruggs Fiddlers frequently play thirds and fifths producing sound that characteristic the bluegrass style Bassists almost always play pizzicato occasionally adopting the slapstyle accentuate the beat bluegrass bass line generally rhythmic alternation between the root and fifth each chord with occasional walking bass excursions Instrumentation has been continuing topic debate Traditional bluegrass performers believe the correct instrumentation that used Bill Monroes band the Blue Grass Boys guitar mandolin fiddle banjo and bass Departures from the traditional instrumentation have included dobro accordion harmonica piano autoharp drums electric guitar and electric versions other common bluegrass instruments resulting what has been referred newgrass Apart from specific instrumentation distinguishing characteristic bluegrass vocal harmony featuring two three four parts often with dissonant modal sound the highest voice see modal frame style described the high lonesome sound Commonly the ordering and layering vocal harmony called the stack standard stack has baritone voice the bottom the lead the middle singing the main melody and tenor the top although stacks can altered especially where female voice included Alison Krauss and Union Station provide good example different harmony stack with baritone and tenor with high lead octave above the standard melody line sung the female vocalist However employing variants the standard trio vocal arrangement they were simply following pattern existing since the early days the genre The Stanley Brothers utilized high baritone part several their trios recorded for Columbia records during their time with that label 19501953 Mandolin player Pee Wee Lambert sang the high baritone above Ralph Stanleys tenor both parts above Carters lead vocal This trio vocal arrangement was variously used other groups well the 1960s Flatt and Scruggs often added fifth part the traditional quartet parts gospel songs the extra part being high baritone doubling the baritone part sung the normal range that voice Tullock aka Cousin Jake providing the part The use high lead with the tenor and baritone below was most famously 